    <h2>Task 1</h2>
    <p>
      Construct two NOI Statements–one that covers last year's actual results
      and a second that projects the upcoming year (which will provide us with
      a 24-month period). Each period should show the breakdown of NOI for the
      total property as well both the Top and Bottom Slices of the property.
    </p>
    <div x-data="{showHint: false}" class="pb-4">
      <button type="button" @click="showHint = true" x-show="!showHint" class="button font-medium">
        Show hint
      </button>
      <div x-show="showHint" class="border border-green-500 rounded-md p-6">
        <span class="text-lg font-medium text-green-500 tracking-wide">Hint</span>
        <p>
          To determine the split between the Bottom Slice and Top Slice of the
          property, we’ll need to use the formula for each of the component lines.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <div>
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 place-items-start">
              <math style="font-weight: 500; font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;font-size: 1.25rem;line-height: 1.75rem;">
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>NOI Property</mi>
                    <mi>as operated</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>-</mo>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>NOI</mi>
                    <mi>theoretical bottom slice</mi>
                  </msub>
                  <mo>=</mo>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>NOI</mi>
                    <mi>theoretical top slice</mi>
                  </msub>
                </mrow>
              </math>
            </div>
          </div>
        </figure>
        <p>
          For last year’s actuals, the total property NOI was <b>$1,980,000</b>
          which can be broken down as <b>$1,528,500</b> Bottom Slice and
          <b>$451,500</b> Top Slice.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the projected NOI Statement for next year, the total property NOI
          is expected to be <b>$2,060,800</b>, which can be broken down as
          <b>$1,559,070</b> Bottom Slice and <b>$501,730</b> Top Slice.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h2>Task 2</h2>
    <p>
      Using the results from your NOI Statements and the Average 24-month NOI,
      what is the expected valuation of the property if the Bottom Slice has a
      Capitalization Rate of 7.0% and the Top Slice has a Capitalization Rate
      of 10.5%?
    </p>
    <p>
      What is the Effective Capitalization Rate for the property?
    </p>
    <div x-data="{showHint: false}" class="pb-4">
      <button type="button" @click="showHint = true" x-show="!showHint" class="button font-medium">
        Show hint
      </button>
      <div x-show="showHint" class="border border-green-500 rounded-md p-6">
        <span class="text-lg font-medium text-green-500 tracking-wide">Hint</span>
        <p>
          Using the results from each of our NOI Statements, we can then
          determine the Average 24-Month NOI for the total property ($2,020,400)
          as well as the Bottom Slice ($1,543,785) and Top Slice ($476,615).
        </p>
        <p>
          To calculate the value of the total property, we need to sum the
          values of each Slice.
        </p>
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1 list-disc pl-12">
          <li class="text-gray-800 text-lg">
            Bottom Slice: the NOI is divided by a 7.0% Capitalization Rate for
            a value of <b>$26,593,262</b>
          </li>
          <li class="text-gray-800 text-lg">
            Top Slice: the NOI is divided by a 10.5% Capitalization Rate for
            a value of <b>$4,539,190</b>
          </li>
          <li class="text-gray-800 text-lg">
            Total Property: <b>$26,593,262</b>, which is the sum of the value
            of the two Slices
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The Effective Capitalization Rate for the property can be calculated
          by dividing the total property NOI by the total property value, which
          gives us a value of 7.60%.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
